Welcome to the=C2=A01,142=C2=A0newly Not Boring people =F0=9F=A4=AF=C2=A0wh=
o have joined us since the last post I wrote in August =E2=80=94 I need to =
take breaks more often! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0153,35=
9 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:
=F0=9F=8E=A7=C2=A0 To get the magic right in your ears, listen on Spotify [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/23376e9b-668d-4d5e-8e83-ffd5a946d956?r=3D9p0=
gt ] or=C2=A0Apple Podcasts [ https://substack.com/redirect/59b39d19-c746-4=
82e-b088-b03875982726?r=3D9p0gt ]
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Polywork [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/4b33c45f-230f-47a3-b358-f263da52d1b6?r=3D9p0gt ]
Polywork [ https://substack.com/redirect/4b33c45f-230f-47a3-b358-f263da52d1=
b6?r=3D9p0gt ] is a place to discover opportunities to collaborate with oth=
er professionals. Existing networks like LinkedIn focus on connecting us to=
 9-5 opportunities =E2=80=94 but where do you go to find opportunities to s=
peak on podcasts? Or discover partners for your side project? Check out who=
 at Google or Netflix is open to angel investing or starting a company? If =
LinkedIn is built for the 9-5 generation, Polywork is built for the collabo=
ration generation.
It=E2=80=99s been in private beta for just over a year, but this week it pu=
blicly launched for everyone, was #1 on Product Hunt, and announced its Ser=
ies B funding. So what=E2=80=99s its magic?
Polywork [ https://substack.com/redirect/4b33c45f-230f-47a3-b358-f263da52d1=
b6?r=3D9p0gt ] understands that as professionals, our list of job titles do=
n=E2=80=99t do a good job of telling our full stories. Furthermore, it=E2=
=80=99s purpose built for professionals who want to connect with one anothe=
r beyond their 9-5. There=E2=80=99s a growing network of amazing profession=
als from places like Figma, Snapchat, and Github all sharing what they want=
 to do =E2=80=94 making it incredibly easy to collaborate with anyone, on a=
nything.
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Monday! Last week, I asked people on Twitter [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/795761b4-f7d5-4300-88c0-48ba0e3ee345?r=3D9p0gt ] for the best essay=
s and blog posts they=E2=80=99ve ever read and they delivered. You should c=
heck out the replies. There=E2=80=99s gold in there.=20
I think as a result of reading so much great stuff, I had more fun writing =
this week=E2=80=99s piece than I=E2=80=99ve had writing in a long time. It =
flowed.=20
I hope you like this one, and if you do, that you=E2=80=99ll share it and s=
pread the magic.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Indistinguishable from Magic [ https://substack.com/redirect/caee1626-51d2-=
4f36-9ff2-1676737adc31?r=3D9p0gt ]
(Click that link =F0=9F=91=86 to read the full thing in your browser)
There=E2=80=99s a famous quote from =E2=80=9CEnglish science-fiction writer=
, science writer, futurist, inventor, undersea explorer, and television ser=
ies host=E2=80=9D Arthur C. Clarke. You probably already know the one I=E2=
=80=99m talking about:=C2=A0
Any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s been quoted so many times that it=E2=80=99s lost its meaning=
=2E =E2=80=9CYeah, yeah, technology can b=
e really cool. I get it.=E2=80=9D Pe=
rsonally, when I read it, I think about the technology itself, but that=E2=
=80=99s not the important part. The important part is the magical experienc=
e a sufficiently advanced technology makes people feel.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s what I mean in an example. Sending a rocket into space with =
people on it and bringing them back to Earth safely, is, at least to my non=
-rocket scientist brain, indistinguishable from magic. But the technology i=
tself wasn=E2=80=99t nearly as magical as watching, two months into COVID l=
ockdowns, SpaceX and NASA send humans to space from American soil for the f=
irst time in nearly a decade.=C2=A0
While the launch itself was a feat of engineering, the fact that watching i=
t could transport me from the tiny apartment we=E2=80=99d been locked in fo=
r two months and into orbit might as well have been a feat of real, honest-=
to-Merlin magic.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve been writing a lot about technology=E2=80=99s role in making t=
he future better, about how it can improve metrics like lifespan and econom=
ic output and lift people out of poverty. As Balaji wrote [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/52414ad9-9214-4240-992b-13e7c02fe174?r=3D9p0gt ], =E2=80=9CI=
f the proximate purpose of technology is to reduce scarcity, the ultimate p=
urpose of technology is to eliminate mortality.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s all=
 incredibly important and I=E2=80=99m going to keep writing about it. But I=
 also think that, technology can play another, equally important role: help=
 people experience magic.
Rocket launches are big, once-in-a-while events, but technology can create =
more quotidian magic, too. Jumping into a chat room with my friends on AIM =
when I was younger was magical. Meeting someone at a party in college and c=
oming home to the Friend Request on Facebook was magical. Pulling up all of=
 the world=E2=80=99s music on Spotify from my phone for the first time was =
magical. Today, getting the prompt right and watching what DALL=E2=80=A2E a=
nd Stable Diffusion come back with is magical. Jumping into a well-curated =
space in OnCyber is magical. Even using the browser I=E2=80=99m using right=
 now =E2=80=93 Arc by The Browser Company =E2=80=93 feels magical.=C2=A0
Magic can, even must, be a strategy for startups. It=E2=80=99s something th=
ey can uniquely create, that incumbents often can=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
Last week, Figma announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/407c8299-9f68-47=
3f-b425-8825de483b02?r=3D9p0gt ] that Adobe was acquiring the company for $=
20 billion (plus an extra $2 billion in potential options).=C2=A0
Figma is just a decade old. It came into a space that Adobe completely domi=
nated. If you had evaluated Figma vs. Adobe at the time, you would have poi=
nted to Adobe=E2=80=99s network effects, the high switching costs for desig=
ners, and its more richly developed product suite. What you might have unde=
restimated was Figma=E2=80=99s magic.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m not a designer. I tried using Photoshop once (evidence below) a=
nd gave up. It was too complicated. There were too many features. I never k=
new what layer to use. Then, when I started writing this newsletter, I trie=
d Figma. It was magic. I could actually do things =E2=80=93 not well, but I=
 could do them =E2=80=93 and all of a sudden, visuals became part of Not Bo=
ring=E2=80=99s identity. All of it, right there in the browser. I, never be=
fore a target customer for a design tool, became part of the TAM. I created=
 more myself, and told other people about Figma, too.=C2=A0
There are a lot of reasons that Figma succeeded in the face of a much bigge=
r competitor to the point that that competitor was forced to pay 50x ARR to=
 stop the advance. Practically everyone in tech has shared their opinion in=
 the past few days. Kevin Kwok [ https://substack.com/redirect/4ab74621-a05=
d-4e6d-8530-bc02aa5bdaf6?r=3D9p0gt ] broke many of those reasons down in hi=
s classic Why Figma Wins [ https://substack.com/redirect/aa99fcf3-cef2-4c13=
-a96b-3454b6dd1c5f?r=3D9p0gt ] and I agree with all of it. But what the pie=
ce doesn=E2=80=99t address =E2=80=93 even though the mechanics Kevin covers=
 are inputs to it =E2=80=93 is the magic powers that Figma gives its users.=
 Just look at all of the results for =E2=80=9CFigma magic=E2=80=9D on Twitt=
er [ https://substack.com/redirect/ab293590-5083-4581-9158-7dd9ab8781a9?r=
=3D9p0gt ]. As if on cue, Adobe=E2=80=99s Chief Product Officer, Scott Bels=
ky, tweeted [ https://substack.com/redirect/f8b76994-636f-4c4e-918c-df40318=
c83a9?r=3D9p0gt ]: =E2=80=9CFigma will continue to operate w/ autonomy, con=
tinuing to work their magic.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAny sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from mag=
ic.=E2=80=9D The sufficiently advanced part of that gets less credit than i=
t deserves, too, and I think it holds the key to why startups have a magic =
advantage over incumbents. Kwok wrote that Figma=E2=80=99s network effects =
were =E2=80=9Cmade possible by Figma=E2=80=99s key early choices like:=C2=
=A0
Architecting Figma to be truly browser-first, instead of just having storag=
e be in the cloud
Their head start in new technologies like WebGL and CRDTs that made this br=
owser-first approach possible=E2=80=9D
Starting with a blank canvas, Figma was able to choose the (right) sufficie=
ntly advanced technologies at that moment in time without worrying about tw=
o decades=E2=80=99 worth of technical debt. As a young startup, it could fo=
cus on creating magic and ride that magic until, one day, it, too, had too =
much technical debt, until we were all too used to its technology to be awe=
d, and until the demands of the public markets forced it to make the kinds =
of practical business-driven decisions that kill the magic.=C2=A0
Design Twitter melted down upon hearing the news of the Adobe acquisition, =
fearing that Adobe would kill everything that made the product beautiful. B=
ut whether Adobe accelerates the downfall or not (and I think both Scott Be=
lsky and Figma CEO Dylan Field are good enough that it won=E2=80=99t), the =
magic would have, eventually, degraded anyway.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s the Magical Startup Circle of Life. A startup, if it=E2=80=99s=
 lucky, creates magic, turns that magic into dollars, and transitions to li=
fe as a successful Big Muggle Company, capable of enormous profits and powe=
r but no longer able to conjure magic. Then a new Magician comes along, usi=
ng sufficiently advanced technology to build something indistinguishable fr=
om magic, and uses that magic as a wedge to challenge the Big Muggle Compan=
y.=C2=A0
My friend Nathan Baschez=E2=80=99s conspiracy theory captures the idea well=
:
When I decided to write a piece on magical tech a few weeks ago, it was mor=
e negative. The draft I started was titled =E2=80=9CWhere Did the Magical T=
ech Go?=E2=80=9D It was inspired by personal frustration and a wave [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/3d8c0dfd-56e6-4251-a0ce-2d97c2ca0bfa?r=3D9p0gt ] o=
f [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c5ba404-fced-400c-a7cc-dc7f018835ae?r=3D=
9p0gt ] tweets [ https://substack.com/redirect/c96fd9e9-bb18-4118-b47b-f59d=
f2a747dc?r=3D9p0gt ] that proved I wasn=E2=80=99t alone.=C2=A0
I was planning to bemoan the loss of magic in the products I once loved and=
 try to figure out why the technology I use isn=E2=80=99t as magical as it =
once was. But that=E2=80=99s not what=E2=80=99s happening. What=E2=80=99s h=
appening is more fascinating. The last generation of magical products has m=
atured, turned into Muggles, and in so doing, has cleared space for a new c=
ohort of Magicians.=C2=A0
So let=E2=80=99s take a trip down Memory Lane to remember and celebrate tho=
se once-magical products, before getting excited all over again about the n=
ew magic being created today.=C2=A0
The Last Era=E2=80=99s Magic
Exactly one decade ago, in the summer of 2012, I taught myself to =E2=80=9C=
code=E2=80=9D and spun up a website for the party bus =E2=80=9Cstartup=E2=
=80=9D I ran, ThrowGo.=C2=A0
Each weekend in the summer, I=E2=80=99d rent party buses to take other youn=
g New Yorkers from the city to Avalon, NJ and the Hamptons. As you can see,=
 the website was horrendous, but to me, it was magical. Instead of having t=
o deal with a wave of texts while at my day job, people could just book dir=
ectly online, and then pay on the bus via cash or a Square reader. Riders c=
ould #throwgo on Instagram and the photos (usually) automatically got pulle=
d into the site, where they could relive half-drunk memories (or hit themse=
lves with an extra dose of FOMO). And with a nifty little Spotify embed, an=
yone could add songs to the playlist that we=E2=80=99d listen to on the rid=
e.
Spotify was particularly magical. I grew up in the era of dial-up and Napst=
er and Limewire. I was used to having to wait minutes while a song download=
ed, then doing the same thing 14-20 times (you could try to do them all at =
once, but then they all slowed down) before burning them onto a CD, which I=
 could play in the car until it got so scratched that it didn=E2=80=99t wor=
k anymore or until I was sick of the songs. Sometimes, I=E2=80=99d download=
 a song and it wasn=E2=80=99t what I wanted. Other times, I couldn=E2=80=99=
t download the song at all. When iTunes came out, it at least guaranteed th=
at I=E2=80=99d get the song I wanted, even if it still took some time to do=
wnload and cost a then-pricey $0.99 per track. It was definitely better, an=
d the iPod, with its 1,000 songs in my pocket, was pretty damn magical.=C2=
=A0
=C2=A0I remember the first time I listened to an iPod. It wasn=E2=80=99t mi=
ne. It was also on a bus, on a school field trip to Killington, Vermont. I =
sat next to my friend Pat Wilkinson, because he was one of my best friends,=
 and also because he=E2=80=99d just bought an iPod. He let me listen to it,=
 and while our taste in music didn=E2=80=99t overlap perfectly (his was mor=
e refined, he had older siblings), I scrolled that scroll pad until I found=
 something that we both liked:
I clicked, the wheel clicked back, and the song played. Magical. But I don=
=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99ve thought about that moment until I weaved my w=
ay there a couple paragraphs ago. Typing =E2=80=9CiTunes=E2=80=9D triggered=
 =E2=80=9CiPod=E2=80=9D in my brain, and the memory came back.=C2=A0
Spotify was a different story. I=E2=80=99ve thought about my first Spotify =
experience a lot. I vividly remember the first time we used Spotify on the =
party bus. It was a Sunday. People were half-asleep, half-dead, just hoping=
 to survive the trip back to the city. But as sometimes happened, a small g=
roup didn=E2=80=99t want to waste the last few party-able hours of the week=
end before heading back to the office.=C2=A0
So I plugged in my phone to the audio jack and connected to the Spotify app=
=2E=C2=A0
I asked my friends Kirk and Nick what they wanted to listen to, we picked a=
 crowd pleaser, searched it, and =E2=80=A6 there it was.=C2=A0
To keep reading about the old magic and the new=E2=80=A6=20
